        <span class="mx-2">/</span>
        <a href="/conveyor-functions/" class="hover:text-white/70">Functions</a>
        <span class="mx-2">/</span>
        <span class="text-white/70">Reject Systems</span>
      </nav>
      <div class="max-w-3xl">
        <div class="section-label text-accent-bright/80 mb-6">Conveyor Function</div>
        <h1 class="font-display text-5xl sm:text-6xl lg:text-7xl font-extrabold text-white tracking-wide uppercase leading-[0.95] mb-8">
          Conveyor <span class="text-accent-bright">Reject</span> Systems
        </h1>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ═══ AIO DEFINITION ═══ -->
  <article>
    <section class="py-12 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="aio-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <p id="aio-heading" class="text-lg text-ink leading-relaxed">
          A conveyor reject system removes non-conforming product from the production line after a metal detector, checkweigher, vision system, or X-ray scanner detects a defect. The reject mechanism activates within 20 to 500 milliseconds of the detection signal, diverting defective product into a locked reject bin while good product continues downstream. Loma Systems, Mettler-Toledo, Eriez, and Fortress Technology manufacture integrated inspection-and-reject conveyor systems for food, pharmaceutical, and consumer goods packaging lines.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ WHY REJECT SYSTEMS MATTER ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="why-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Critical Function</div>
        <h2 id="why-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Why Reject Systems <span class="text-accent">Matter</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <p>
            Reject systems are the last line of defense between a defective product and the consumer. A metal detector that finds contamination means nothing if the reject mechanism fails to remove that product from the line. Regulatory bodies including the FDA, USDA, and GFSI-benchmarked food safety schemes (SQF, BRC, FSSC 22000) require documented proof that reject systems reliably remove every detected defect.
          </p>
          <p>
            Reject system failures cause two types of costly events. <strong class="text-ink">False passes</strong> , contaminated product reaches the consumer, triggering recalls, liability, and brand damage. <strong class="text-ink">False rejects</strong> , good product diverts into the reject bin, wasting material and reducing yield. A well-designed reject system minimizes both. The detection device determines false pass and false reject rates. The reject mechanism determines whether a true detection results in reliable product removal.
          </p>
          <p>
            Most <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">food packaging lines</a> place reject systems at two to four points: after the metal detector (mandatory for most retailers), after the checkweigher (weight compliance), after the vision system (label and package integrity), and optionally after the X-ray system (foreign object detection). Each reject point requires its own mechanism, bin, and confirmation sensor.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ REJECT MECHANISM TYPES ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="types-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Mechanism Types</div>
        <h2 id="types-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Reject Mechanism <span class="text-accent">Types</span>
        </h2>

        <div class="space-y-12">
          <!-- Air Blast -->
          <div>
            <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mb-4">Air Blast Reject</h3>
            <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-4">
              <p>
                Air blast rejects use a burst of compressed air to blow product off the conveyor into a reject bin. A solenoid valve fires one or more air nozzles mounted beside or above the conveyor. Response time is 20–50ms , the fastest of all reject types. Air blast rejects handle lightweight products (under 500g) at high speeds (up to 400+ FPM).
              </p>
              <p>
                Air blast works best for small, lightweight items: individual snack bags, pouches, candy bars, blister packs, and loose confectionery. The air pulse must generate enough force to push the product clear of the belt before the next product arrives. Product spacing (gap between products) must be wide enough that the air blast does not deflect adjacent good product. A product gap of at least 1.5x the air pulse duration prevents collateral rejection.
              </p>
              <p>
                Limitations: air blast cannot reject heavy products (cases, bottles, jars). Compressed air consumption adds operating cost , a high-reject-rate line uses significant air volume. In dusty environments, the air blast can scatter particulates. Air blast rejects require a clean, dry compressed air supply (instrument-grade, filtered to 5 microns minimum) to prevent nozzle clogging.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Pusher Arm -->
          <div>
            <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mb-4">Pusher Arm Reject</h3>
            <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-4">
              <p>
                Pusher arm rejects use a pneumatic or servo-driven cylinder to push product off the side of the conveyor. The arm extends across the belt, contacts the product, and pushes it into a reject chute or bin. Response time is 50–150ms. Pusher arms handle products from 50g to 25kg , the workhorse reject for cases, cartons, bottles, jars, and cans.
              </p>
              <p>
                Pusher arm design must match the product's height, width, and center of gravity. The contact pad (the surface that touches the product) should be wide enough to push the product without tipping it. Products with a high center of gravity (tall bottles, upright cartons) may need a two-level pusher , one pad contacts the base, another contacts the upper portion. Mettler-Toledo and Loma Systems offer pusher arm rejects as standard options on their checkweigher and metal detector conveyor systems.
              </p>
              <p>
                The pusher arm must fully retract before the next good product arrives. At high speeds with tight product spacing, the retract time limits throughput. Servo-driven pushers retract faster than pneumatic and offer programmable stroke length for different product widths. However, servo pushers cost significantly more than pneumatic.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Diverter Gate -->
          <div>
            <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mb-4">Diverter Gate / Sweep Arm Reject</h3>
            <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-4">
              <p>
                Diverter gate rejects use a pivoting arm or gate that swings across the conveyor path, sweeping product off the side. The gate pivots from one side of the conveyor and sweeps product to the opposite side into a reject chute. Response time is 100–300ms. Diverter gates handle medium to heavy products (1–50kg) including cases, trays, and bundled products.
              </p>
              <p>
                Diverter gates excel at rejecting products that arrive in groups (multi-packs, shrink-wrapped bundles) because the sweeping motion clears the full belt width. The gate design can include a curved guide surface that redirects product smoothly rather than pushing against it , reducing impact damage to the product and the mechanism.
              </p>
              <p>
                For <a href="/industries/packaging-line-conveyors/pallet/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">pallet conveyor</a> applications, heavy-duty diverter gates reject entire cases or pallets. These gates use servo motors or hydraulic cylinders rather than pneumatics to handle the high forces required.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Drop-Out Belt -->
          <div>
            <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mb-4">Drop-Out (Retractable) Belt Reject</h3>
            <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-4">
              <p>
                Drop-out belt rejects remove a section of the conveyor belt when a defect triggers rejection. The belt section either drops away (hinged), retracts laterally, or accelerates forward to open a gap. Product falls through the opening into a reject bin below the conveyor. Response time is 150–500ms , slower than other methods but with a key advantage: no lateral force touches the product.
              </p>
              <p>
                Drop-out belts suit products that cannot tolerate side pushing , open trays, unwrapped food, loose product on a belt. They also reject products of any weight, from lightweight pouches to heavy cases, because gravity does the work. The drop-out section must be long enough to clear the entire product before closing. Eriez and Fortress Technology offer integrated metal detector/drop-out belt systems for food processing.
              </p>
              <p>
                The primary limitation is speed. The belt must open, the product must clear the gap, and the belt must close before the next product arrives. At high speeds with tight product spacing, drop-out belts cannot cycle fast enough. A minimum product gap of 300–500mm is typical.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ COMPARISON TABLE ═══ -->
