                <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Mechanism</th>
                <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Response Time</th>
                <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Product Weight</th>
                <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Product Contact</th>
                <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Relative Cost</th>
                <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4">Best For</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="text-base text-ink-muted">
              <tr class="border-b border-border">
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Air Blast</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">20–50 ms</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">&#x3C; 500g</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4">None (air only)</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">$</td>
                <td class="py-4">Snack bags, pouches, blister packs</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-border">
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Pusher Arm</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">50–150 ms</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">50g–25 kg</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4">Side contact</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">$$</td>
                <td class="py-4">Bottles, jars, cartons, cases</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-border">
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Diverter Gate</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">100–300 ms</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">1–50 kg</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4">Sweep contact</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">$$–$$$</td>
                <td class="py-4">Cases, bundles, multi-packs</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Drop-Out Belt</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">150–500 ms</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">Any weight</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4">None (gravity)</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">$$$</td>
                <td class="py-4">Open trays, unwrapped food, fragile</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm text-ink-muted mt-4">Relative cost: $ = lowest, $$$$ = highest. <a href="/resources/conveyor-cost-guide/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">See full cost guide</a>.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ INSPECTION DEVICE INTEGRATION ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="integration-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Integration</div>
        <h2 id="integration-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Inspection Device <span class="text-accent">Integration</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-4 mb-3">Metal Detector Integration</h3>
          <p>
            Metal detectors scan product for ferrous, non-ferrous, and stainless steel contamination. The detector sends a reject signal to the reject mechanism controller after detecting metal. The time delay between detection and reject activation accounts for the distance the product must travel from the detector aperture to the reject point. This delay , called the reject delay or product track time , must be calculated precisely. Too short, and the reject fires before the contaminated product arrives. Too long, and the product passes the reject point.
          </p>
          <p>
            Loma Systems' IQ4 series, Mettler-Toledo's Profile Advantage, and Fortress Technology's Interceptor line integrate metal detection with built-in conveyor and reject systems. These combination units mount the metal detector, conveyor belt, and reject mechanism on a single frame, ensuring consistent detector-to-reject distance and eliminating integration timing issues.
          </p>
          <!-- VERIFY: Loma IQ4 series current model designation -->

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-8 mb-3">Checkweigher Integration</h3>
          <p>
            Checkweighers weigh every product in motion and reject units outside the target weight range (underweight or overweight). The checkweigher's built-in reject system , typically a pusher arm or air blast , fires immediately after the weigh cell determines the product is out of spec. Checkweighers require a controlled infeed spacing to ensure only one product occupies the weigh cell at a time. An <a href="/conveyor-functions/indexing-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">indexing conveyor</a> or spacing belt upstream provides this consistent product gap.
          </p>
          <p>
            Mettler-Toledo's C-Series and Ishida's DACS checkweighers include integrated reject systems with reject confirmation sensors. The reject confirmation sensor verifies that the rejected product left the belt and entered the reject bin. If confirmation fails, the checkweigher alarms and optionally stops the line , a critical safety feature for products sold by weight (meat, cheese, produce).
          </p>
          <!-- VERIFY: Ishida DACS current model range and reject confirmation feature set -->

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-8 mb-3">Vision System Integration</h3>
          <p>
            <a href="/conveyor-functions/inspection-detection/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Vision inspection systems</a> check labels (presence, position, readability, content), package integrity (seal quality, fill level, cap presence), and cosmetic defects (color, surface damage). The vision camera captures an image, the software processes it (5–50ms), and the system sends a pass/fail signal to the reject controller. Vision rejects require precise product tracking because the camera and reject point may be separated by 12–36 inches of conveyor.
          </p>
          <p>
            Product tracking uses either an encoder (measuring belt travel distance from camera to reject) or a photoeye (detecting product arrival at the reject point). Encoder-based tracking is more reliable at variable speeds. The reject controller calculates when the defective product will reach the reject mechanism and fires at the correct moment. For systems integrating vision with other inspection devices, see the <a href="/resources/automated-conveyor-systems/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">automated conveyor systems</a> guide.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-8 mb-3">X-Ray System Integration</h3>
          <p>
            X-ray inspection detects foreign objects that metal detectors miss , glass, stone, bone, dense plastics, and rubber. X-ray systems also perform mass estimation, fill level checking, and component counting. Reject mechanisms for X-ray systems follow the same principles as metal detector rejects. Eriez and Mettler-Toledo supply X-ray inspection systems with integrated conveyor and reject for food and pharmaceutical lines.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ REJECT CONFIRMATION & COMPLIANCE ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="confirm-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Compliance</div>
        <h2 id="confirm-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Reject Confirmation &#x26; <span class="text-accent">Compliance</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <p>
            Reject confirmation is the process of verifying that a rejected product actually left the main conveyor. A sensor (photoeye or proximity switch) monitors the reject bin or chute. When the reject mechanism fires, the confirmation sensor expects to detect a product entering the reject bin within a defined time window. Three outcomes are possible:
          </p>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-3 ml-2">
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Confirmed reject:</strong> The sensor detects the product in the bin. The system logs the event and continues running. Normal operation.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Failed reject (no confirmation):</strong> The sensor does not detect a product in the bin. The contaminated product may still be on the main conveyor. The system triggers an alarm and , depending on configuration , stops the line. This is the critical safety event that reject confirmation exists to catch.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">False confirmation:</strong> The sensor detects a product in the bin, but it was not the target product (e.g., a different product fell into the bin accidentally). Rare, but possible if the reject bin sensor lacks specificity.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            Major retailers (Walmart, Costco, Kroger, Aldi) and food safety audit standards (BRC Global Standard for Food Safety, SQF Code) increasingly mandate reject confirmation on metal detector and X-ray reject systems. Some retailers specify that the line must stop automatically on a failed reject confirmation , manual acknowledgment alone is insufficient.
          </p>
          <p>
            The reject bin must be locked to prevent operators from retrieving rejected product and returning it to the line. Keyed locks, electronic latches tied to the PLC, and tamper-evident seals all serve this purpose. Loma Systems, Fortress Technology, and Mettler-Toledo offer locked reject bins with confirmation sensors as standard equipment on their <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">food-grade inspection systems</a>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ CONVEYOR DESIGN FOR REJECT ZONES ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="design-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Conveyor Design</div>
        <h2 id="design-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Conveyor Design for <span class="text-accent">Reject Zones</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <p>
            The conveyor section carrying product through the reject zone requires specific design features that differ from standard transport conveyors:
          </p>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-3 ml-2">
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Consistent speed:</strong> Product tracking from detector to reject relies on known belt speed. VFD-controlled conveyors with encoder feedback maintain speed within ±1%, ensuring accurate reject timing. Speed variation causes missed rejects or good-product rejects.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Adequate product spacing:</strong> Each product must be separated by enough gap to allow the reject mechanism to fire and retract between products. Minimum gap depends on the mechanism: air blast needs 25–50mm; pusher arms need 75–150mm; drop-out belts need 300–500mm. A spacing conveyor or <a href="/conveyor-functions/indexing-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">indexing section</a> upstream creates the required gap.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Side-clearance for pusher rejects:</strong> The reject side of the conveyor needs clear space for the reject chute and bin. The opposite side needs an open path for the pusher arm stroke. Conveyor frame height must allow the reject bin to fit underneath or beside the belt.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Washdown construction:</strong> Reject zones in <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/sanitary/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">sanitary food environments</a> need stainless steel frames, IP69K motors, and belt designs that allow tool-free removal for cleaning. Reject bin interiors must be accessible for sanitation.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            The conveyor section immediately downstream of the reject must not accumulate product during a reject event. If the reject mechanism removes a product, the resulting gap in the product stream should flow through to the next machine without causing a fault. <a href="/conveyor-types/accumulation-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Accumulation conveyors</a> downstream absorb the intermittent gaps created by rejects.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ SELECTION CRITERIA ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="selection-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Selection Guide</div>
        <h2 id="selection-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Selecting a <span class="text-accent">Reject System</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <p>
            Match the reject mechanism to five parameters:
          </p>
          <ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 ml-2">
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Product weight and size.</strong> Air blast for products under 500g. Pusher arm for 50g–25kg. Diverter gate for 1–50kg. Drop-out belt for any weight, especially products that cannot tolerate lateral contact.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Conveyor speed and product spacing.</strong> Higher speed demands faster mechanism response. Calculate the product transit time from detector to reject: Transit time = Distance (inches) / Speed (inches/sec). The mechanism must complete its cycle within this window.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Reject rate.</strong> High reject rates (>2%) mean the mechanism cycles frequently. Pneumatic mechanisms consume more compressed air; electrical mechanisms consume more power. High reject rates also fill the reject bin faster , size the bin for the expected reject volume per shift.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Compliance requirements.</strong> Food and pharmaceutical applications require reject confirmation sensors, locked reject bins, and event logging. Ensure the reject system's data output integrates with your line PLC and quality management system.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Environment.</strong> <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/sanitary/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Washdown environments</a> require stainless steel construction and IP69K ratings. Dry environments accept standard industrial construction.</li>
          </ol>
          <p>
            For cost planning across your entire conveyor system, including reject stations, see the <a href="/resources/conveyor-cost-guide/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">conveyor cost guide</a>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

